1 AMEND House Committee Substitute for House Bill Nos. 3068 & 3049, Page 7, Section 43.530,
2 Line 23, by inserting after all of said section and line the following:
3
4 "301.287. 1. This section shall be known and referred to as "Mason's Law".
5 2. Beginning January 1, 2027, a resident of this state with a health condition or disability
6 that limits or impairs the ability to effectively communicate with law enforcement may, at any
7 time, apply to the department of revenue for a designation that shall be associated with the
8 person's driver's license issued under chapter 302 and motor vehicle license plate or plates issued
9 under this chapter and available to law enforcement under the Missouri uniform law enforcement
10 system (MULES) established under chapter 43.
11 3. The initial application, which shall be on a form prescribed by the department and
12 made available on the department's website, shall by signed by a physician licensed under
13 chapter 334, or a psychologist licensed under chapter 337, certifying that:
14 (1) The applicant or the applicant's child, parent, or spouse has a physical or mental
15 health condition that is likely to impair the ability to effectively communicate with law
16 enforcement; and
17 (2) The physician or psychologist has determined that the applicant or the applicant's
18 child, parent, or spouse will have the communication impairment for at least five years.
19 4. Upon submission of an application and approval by the department, the department
20 shall prepare an entry in the department's records that is accessible to law enforcement via
21 MULES and that indicates that the applicant or the applicant's child, parent, or spouse has a
22 physical or mental health condition that may impair the ability to effectively communicate with
23 law enforcement. Such entry as related to the applicant’s driver’s license shall remain active
24 until the expiration of their driver’s license. Such entry as related to the applicant’s motor
25 vehicle license plate or plates shall remain active for a period of five years, unless the applicant
26 requests that such designation be removed from the records. Upon expiration of the five-year
27 period, the designation in the department's records may be reactivated upon the filing of a
28 renewal form with the department signed by a physician licensed under chapter 334, or a
29 psychologist licensed under chapter 337, certifying that:
30 (1) The applicant or the applicant's child, parent, or spouse has a physical or mental
31 health condition that is likely to impair the ability to effectively communicate with law
32 enforcement; and
